ns and repetitions, Saenz addresses the reader, the beloved, and death in one extended lyrical gesture. The poems are brazenly affecting. Their semantic innovation is notable in the odd heterogeneity of formal and tonal structures that careen unabashedly between modes and moods; now archly lyrical, now arcanely symbolic, now colloquial, now trancelike. As Saenz's reputation continues to grow throughout the world, these inspired translations and the accompanying Spanish texts faithfully convey the poet's unique vision and voice to English-speaking readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBolivian poetryy20th century. 0aPoetry, BolivianvTranslations into English. 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aanthology.  aapocalyptic.  abaroque.  abisexuality.  abolivia.  abolivian cultures.  abolivian poet.  adramatic.  aenglish translation.  afamous authors.  afamous poets.  ainternational literature.  ala paz.  algbtq.  alit scholars.  alit students.  alit studies.  aliterary critics.  alyrical poetry.  amodern art.  amodern poetry.  amystical.  aoccult.  aodes.  apoetry book.  apoetry collection.  apoetry textbook.  apoets.  apsychological.  asexuality.  aspanish poetry.  asymbolic.  avisionary.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023048440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093602740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936027423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520936027/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY